1️⃣ Management Groups (Top Governance Layer)
4
Definition

A Management Group (MG) is a governance container for multiple subscriptions.

It allows you to apply:

Azure Policies

RBAC permissions

Compliance rules

once, and they automatically apply to all child subscriptions.

Why Enterprises Use Management Groups

Without MGs:

You must configure:

policies

RBAC

security controls

for every subscription individually.

If a company has:

50 subscriptions

200 subscriptions

500 subscriptions

That becomes impossible to manage.

MGs allow central governance at scale.

Policy Inheritance

Example:

If a policy is assigned at Platform MG:

Platform MG
   └── Platform Subscription
   └── Dev Subscription
   └── Prod Subscription

That policy automatically applies to:

Platform

Dev

Prod

No duplication needed.

2️⃣ Subscriptions (Billing + Isolation Boundary)
Definition

A subscription is:

a billing boundary

a security isolation boundary

a deployment container

All resources must exist inside a subscription.

Why Enterprises Use Multiple Subscriptions

Because they provide:

1️⃣ Isolation

Dev workloads cannot affect Prod.

2️⃣ Billing separation

Each environment can have its own budget.

3️⃣ Security control

RBAC can be different per subscription.

4️⃣ Scaling

Large companies often have hundreds of subscriptions.

In Your Project

You will create three subscriptions conceptually:

Platform Subscription
Dev Subscription
Prod Subscription

Platform Subscription

Contains shared infrastructure:

Hub VNet

Firewall

Log Analytics

Monitoring

DNS

Shared Key Vault

Managed by platform team only.

Dev Subscription

Contains:

development workloads

testing environments

staging services

More relaxed access.

Prod Subscription

Contains:

production applications

customer data

critical services

Strict access and policies.

3️⃣ Resource Groups (Deployment Organization)
Definition

A Resource Group (RG) is a logical container inside a subscription.

It groups related resources.

Example:

Subscription: Prod

Resource Group: prod-network
   VNet
   Firewall

Resource Group: prod-app1
   VM
   Storage
   KeyVault
Why Resource Groups Exist

They help with:

resource organization

lifecycle management

access control

Important Rule

RBAC and policies can be applied at:

Management Group

Subscription

Resource Group

Individual Resource

Inheritance flows downward.

4️⃣ Enterprise Governance Hierarchy

Here is the typical enterprise model.

Tenant Root Management Group
│
├── Platform Management Group
│       └── Platform Subscription
│
├── Production Management Group
│       └── Prod Subscription
│
└── Development Management Group
        └── Dev Subscription

This structure gives:

governance inheritance

environment isolation

centralized control

5️⃣ Why This Structure Works
Governance at scale
Policies applied at MG level propagate automatically.
Security separation
Prod policies can be stricter than Dev.
Clear ownership
Platform team owns:
networking
monitoring
security
App teams own workloads.

- Why policies should be assigned at the Management Group level instead of subscription level.
Policies should be assigned at the Management Group (MG) level because governance must be applied consistently across multiple subscriptions.

- Why Dev and Prod must be separate subscriptions.
We might have different budget for dev and prod and we might also have to loose some policy or restrict some policy on dev or prod

- Why shared services (firewall, logging) should live in a Platform subscription.
Because it is managed centrally, and it is a shared infrastructure.

- If a company grows to 20 applications, what changes in this hierarchy?
only workload layer, not platform layer